│                                                                                        │
│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                            │
│                                                                                        │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                                        │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                            │
│ The crash occurs in ConstantExpr::getCast due to an invalid constantexpr cast          │
│ generated by the SLP vectorizer when handling a vectorized cast node. Specifically,    │
│ IRBuilder::CreateCast is invoked with an opcode and types that are incompatible:       │
│ attempting to cast a <2 x i1> constant to <2 x i32> using an integer Trunc (or         │
│ BitCast) operation, which is invalid.                                                  │
│                                                                                        │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                                │
│ From the debug-only SLP log, the pass decides to vectorize a chain of stores and a     │
│ series of ands and casts. During vectorization of a Cast instruction (case             │
│ Instruction::Cast), the pass computes VecOpcode based on the original scalar cast      │
│ (CI->getOpcode()) and type-size heuristics and MinBWs demotion info. The debugger      │
│ reveals that at the point of the crash: C is a constant <2 x i1> zeroinitializer;      │
│ destination Ty is <2 x i32>; oc (opcode) is 38 (a cast op, consistent with Trunc). The │
│ pass reached the "Diamond merged" message just before the assertion, which is emitted  │
│ in the cast case block we inspected. The types confirm that we're trying to apply a    │
│ Trunc on a vector of i1 to widen to i32, which is invalid. Alternatively, if it were   │
│ BitCast, it would also be invalid because bitcast requires equal total bit size.       │
│                                                                                        │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                                │
│ The logic selecting VecOpcode in BoUpSLP::vectorizeTree for Instruction::Cast is       │
│ flawed when the operand type of the vectorized input (InVec) has been demoted to a     │
│ narrower integer type (e.g., i1) via MinBWs or other heuristics, but MinBWs            │
│ information is not present (SrcIt/It not found) for this node. The current code only   │
│ switches to BitCast if widths are equal, Trunc if destination width < source width,    │
│ and SExt/ZExt only if MinBWs entries exist (It or SrcIt). If the destination scalar    │
│ width is greater than the source scalar width (BWSz > SrcBWSz) and neither It nor      │
│ SrcIt are present, the code leaves VecOpcode as the original scalar CI->getOpcode()    │
│ (e.g., Trunc), which is inappropriate after demotion of the operand: widening should   │
│ use ZExt/SExt, not Trunc. This leads IRBuilder to attempt an invalid cast (Trunc or    │
│ BitCast) from <2 x i1> to <2 x i32>, triggering the assertion.                         │
│                                                                                        │
│ Concretely, we observed:                                                               │
│ - InVec type: <2 x i1>                                                                 │
│ - VecTy (destination): <2 x i32>                                                       │
│ - VecOpcode remained CastOpsBegin/Trunc (38), causing Builder.CreateCast(Trunc, <2 x   │
│ i1>, <2 x i32>), which violates castIsValid.                                           │
│ - The selection logic only assigns SExt/ZExt when MinBWs info exists, but in our case  │
│ it doesn't, leaving an invalid opcode.                                                 │
│                                                                                        │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                             │
│ Edit BoUpSLP::vectorizeTree in the Instruction::Cast case to correctly handle widening │
│ when the vectorized operand element type is narrower than the destination element      │
│ type, even if MinBWs does not provide entries. Specifically, after computing BWSz and  │
│ SrcBWSz, add an else-if branch to set VecOpcode to a widening extend (defaulting to    │
│ ZExt if signedness is not known) when BWSz > SrcBWSz and neither It nor SrcIt are      │
│ available.                                                                             │
│                                                                                        │
│ Edit at llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp lines 13458-13469:             │
│ - Current logic:                                                                       │
│   - if (BWSz == SrcBWSz) VecOpcode = BitCast;                                          │
│   - else if (BWSz < SrcBWSz) VecOpcode = Trunc;                                        │
│   - else if (It != MinBWs.end()) choose SExt/ZExt;                                     │
│   - else if (SrcIt != MinBWs.end()) choose SExt/ZExt.                                  │
│   - Missing: handling of BWSz > SrcBWSz when MinBWs don't have entries.                │
│                                                                                        │
│ - Change: add an else clause for (BWSz > SrcBWSz) to set VecOpcode = ZExt as a safe    │
│ default for integer widening casts when neither It nor SrcIt exists. Alternatively, if │
│ signedness can be inferred from the original cast opcode (e.g., SIToFP implies         │
│ signed), we could use SExt when the original opcode was sign-sensitive. For this       │
│ minimal fix, default to ZExt to avoid invalid casts.                                   │
│                                                                                        │
│ Pseudocode adjustment:                                                                 │
│   } else if (BWSz < SrcBWSz) {                                                         │
│     VecOpcode = Instruction::Trunc;                                                    │
│   } else if (It != MinBWs.end()) {                                                     │
│     ... // existing                                                                    │
│   } else if (SrcIt != MinBWs.end()) {                                                  │
│     ... // existing                                                                    │
│   } else {                                                                             │
│     assert(BWSz > SrcBWSz && "Invalid cast!");                                         │
│     VecOpcode = Instruction::ZExt; // default widening when demotion occurred but no   │
│ MinBWs hints                                                                           │
│   }                                                                                    │
│                                                                                        │
│ This ensures that when the demoted InVec element type is narrower than the destination │
│ type, we perform a valid widening cast rather than attempting Trunc/BitCast.           │
│                                                                                        │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                         │
│ By adding a fallback to use ZExt for widening when MinBWs information is absent, we    │
│ prevent the SLP vectorizer from generating invalid casts during vectorization of       │
│ demoted operands in cast instructions. This fix addresses the root cause of the        │
│ assertion in ConstantExpr::getCast and will allow the pass to emit a correct IR: <2 x  │
│ i1> -> <2 x i32> via zext, avoiding the abort.                                         │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                                        │
│                                                                                        │
