  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe crash occurs in ConstantExpr::getCast
due to an invalid constantexpr cast generated by the SLP vectorizer when handling a
vectorized cast node. Specifically, IRBuilder::CreateCast is invoked with an opcode and
types that are incompatible: attempting to cast a <2 x i1> constant to <2 x i32> using an
integer Trunc (or BitCast) operation, which is invalid.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nFrom
the debug-only SLP log, the pass decides to vectorize a chain of stores and a series of
ands and casts. During vectorization of a Cast instruction (case Instruction::Cast), the
pass computes VecOpcode based on the original scalar cast (CI->getOpcode()) and type-size
heuristics and MinBWs demotion info. The debugger reveals that at the point of the crash:
C is a constant <2 x i1> zeroinitializer; destination Ty is <2 x i32>; oc (opcode) is 38
(a cast op, consistent with Trunc). The pass reached the \"Diamond merged\" message just
before the assertion, which is emitted in the cast case block we inspected. The types
confirm that we're trying to apply a Trunc on a vector of i1 to widen to i32, which is
invalid. Alternatively, if it were BitCast, it would also be invalid because bitcast
requires equal total bit size.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nThe logic selecting VecOpcode
in BoUpSLP::vectorizeTree for Instruction::Cast is flawed when the operand type of the
vectorized input (InVec) has been demoted to a narrower integer type (e.g., i1) via MinBWs
or other heuristics, but MinBWs information is not present (SrcIt/It not found) for this
node. The current code only switches to BitCast if widths are equal, Trunc if destination
width < source width, and SExt/ZExt only if MinBWs entries exist (It or SrcIt). If the
destination scalar width is greater than the source scalar width (BWSz > SrcBWSz) and
neither It nor SrcIt are present, the code leaves VecOpcode as the original scalar
CI->getOpcode() (e.g., Trunc), which is inappropriate after demotion of the operand:
widening should use ZExt/SExt, not Trunc. This leads IRBuilder to attempt an invalid cast
(Trunc or BitCast) from <2 x i1> to <2 x i32>, triggering the assertion.\n\nConcretely, we
observed:\n- InVec type: <2 x i1>\n- VecTy (destination): <2 x i32>\n- VecOpcode remained
CastOpsBegin/Trunc (38), causing Builder.CreateCast(Trunc, <2 x i1>, <2 x i32>), which
violates castIsValid.\n- The selection logic only assigns SExt/ZExt when MinBWs info
exists, but in our case it doesn't, leaving an invalid opcode.\n\n4. Proposed Edit
Point(s):\nEdit BoUpSLP::vectorizeTree in the Instruction::Cast case to correctly handle
widening when the vectorized operand element type is narrower than the destination element
type, even if MinBWs does not provide entries. Specifically, after computing BWSz and
SrcBWSz, add an else-if branch to set VecOpcode to a widening extend (defaulting to ZExt
if signedness is not known) when BWSz > SrcBWSz and neither It nor SrcIt are
available.\n\nEdit at llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp lines
13458-13469:\n- Current logic:\n  - if (BWSz == SrcBWSz) VecOpcode = BitCast;\n  - else if
(BWSz < SrcBWSz) VecOpcode = Trunc;\n  - else if (It != MinBWs.end()) choose SExt/ZExt;\n
- else if (SrcIt != MinBWs.end()) choose SExt/ZExt.\n  - Missing: handling of BWSz >
SrcBWSz when MinBWs don't have entries.\n\n- Change: add an else clause for (BWSz >
SrcBWSz) to set VecOpcode = ZExt as a safe default for integer widening casts when neither
It nor SrcIt exists. Alternatively, if signedness can be inferred from the original cast
opcode (e.g., SIToFP implies signed), we could use SExt when the original opcode was
sign-sensitive. For this minimal fix, default to ZExt to avoid invalid
casts.\n\nPseudocode adjustment:\n  } else if (BWSz < SrcBWSz) {\n    VecOpcode =
Instruction::Trunc;\n  } else if (It != MinBWs.end()) {\n    ... // existing\n  } else if
(SrcIt != MinBWs.end()) {\n    ... // existing\n  } else {\n    assert(BWSz > SrcBWSz &&
\"Invalid cast!\");\n    VecOpcode = Instruction::ZExt; // default widening when demotion
occurred but no MinBWs hints\n  }\n\nThis ensures that when the demoted InVec element type
is narrower than the destination type, we perform a valid widening cast rather than
attempting Trunc/BitCast.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nBy adding a fallback to use ZExt for widening
when MinBWs information is absent, we prevent the SLP vectorizer from generating invalid
casts during vectorization of demoted operands in cast instructions. This fix addresses
the root cause of the assertion in ConstantExpr::getCast and will allow the pass to emit a
correct IR: <2 x i1> -> <2 x i32> via zext, avoiding the abort.",
